Further evidence that a negative AF component coexists with a negative SC component, with the former dominating at higher fluence is shown in Fig. \ref{Fig 2}.  If only one component were present, $\Delta R/R|_{max} \propto n_{ph}$, where n is the number of photoexcited quasiparticles.  As discussed in Ref. \cite{Torchinsky:PnictideUltrafast} $\gamma = B n_{ph} + 2 B n_{th}$, where $n_{th}$ is the number of thermally excited quasiparticles.  In Fig. \ref{Fig 2}(a), the lowest temperatures yield negative y-intercepts which would imply a negative $n_{th}$, which is unphysical.  Thus, the x-axis of Fig. \ref{Fig 2}(a) is an overestimate of $n_{ph}$, with the difference likely corresponding to a small AF component, which is resolved clearly in x$=$0.11 because it is a different sign from the superconducting component.  This negative intercept is seen clearly in Fig. \ref{Fig 2}(c), and when this offset is included, this analysis yields a temperature dependence of $\gamma_{th}$ consistent with the power law and the gap magnitude extracted in the manuscript.  Notably, these data, at sufficiently low fluence, are consistent with bimolecular recombination in a superconductor because the slope, B, is temperature independent until close to T$_c$.

