\section{Temperature dependence of relaxation \textit{time}}
In the manuscript, dynamics are described in terms of relaxation rates.  Fig. \ref{Fig 3} shows relaxation times, $\tau$, across T$_c$ for x=0.08, and plotting data this way better captures sensitivity to T$_c$.  Below T$_c$, $\tau$ begins to rise more rapidly and by the lowest temperature, $\tau$ has increased by an order of magnitude relative to the value right above T$_c$.
\begin{figure}[H]
\includegraphics [type=eps,ext=.eps,read=.eps,clip, width=3 in]{x08_tau_vs_temperature}
\centering
\caption[Fig 3] {\label{Fig 3} Temperature dependence of $\tau = 1/\gamma$ for x=0.08. Below T$_c$, $\tau$ begins to rise more rapidly. Pump fluence was 0.33 $\mu J/cm^2$}
\end{figure}

\section{T$>$T$_c$: PCCO}
Fluence dependence of relaxation rates \textit{above} T$_c$ appear to be ubiquitous in electron-doped cuprates, as the same is observed in PCCO films (x=0.14), as shown in Fig. \ref{Fig 4}.  This behavior is distinct from hole-doped cuprates.
